    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Generator-Critic Loop with Hard Cap and Delta Exit</title>

    <summary>Wrap generation in Generator → Critic → Generator loop with hard cap of 3 iterations. Exit on critic veto, plateau, or cap. Use cheap models for rubric criticism.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Reflection-style loops add real quality on open-ended tasks (writing, codegen, structured extraction with rubrics) — but unbounded reflection is the most common cost trap in production agent stacks. Empirically (Reflection Agents, langchain.com/blog), iteration 2 captures roughly 70-80% of the achievable lift, iteration 3 adds 10-15%, and iterations 4+ contribute below the noise floor. A hard cap of 3 plus an explicit `should_continue` flag from the critic gives bounded latency and an auditable stopping criterion. Cheap-critic-on-rubric is justified by the same data: rubric scoring is a constrained classification task, not free-form reasoning.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Codegen agents that compile/lint/test their own output before returning.</item>
        <item>Copywriting / summarization with a clear rubric (length, voice, audience).</item>
        <item>Structured extraction where a critic verifies all required fields are populated and citations exist.</item>
        <item>Self-correcting RAG: critic checks each answer against retrieved chunks before the answer ships.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Latency-critical paths (chat completions visible to a user) — the second pass doubles wall time.</item>
        <item>Tool-calling agents where ground truth comes from the tool result, not a critic — adding a critic creates two truths and confusion.</item>
        <item>Trivial outputs that consistently pass on iteration 1 — measure the actual lift; if iteration 2 changes less than 2% of cases, kill the loop.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="three-exit-conditions">
      <p>An unbounded reflection loop is the single most common reason production agents overspend. Bounding by iteration count alone is too rigid — the critic should be allowed to short-circuit when satisfied, and a plateau detector kills runs that stop improving.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Generator-Critic loops must exit on the first true condition: (1) critic returns should_continue=False, (2) score delta vs the prior iteration is below epsilon for 2 consecutive iterations, (3) iteration count reaches the hard cap (default 3, never above 5).</statement>
        <rationale>Empirical reflection studies (LangChain Reflection Agents) show iteration 2 captures most of the lift, iteration 3 adds the long tail, and iterations 4+ contribute below the noise floor. Three independent stop conditions cover correctness (critic veto), efficiency (plateau), and safety (cap).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Cap, veto, and plateau all checked">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
output = generate(prompt)
prev_score = -1
for i in range(MAX_ITERS := 3):
    critique = critic(output, prompt)               # structured: score + should_continue
    if not critique.should_continue:
        break
    if i > 0 and abs(critique.score - prev_score) < EPSILON:
        break
    output = generate(prompt, feedback=critique.feedback)
    prev_score = critique.score
return output
        ]]></code>
        <note>Cap, veto, and plateau all checked. Loop exits early when any one fires.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="No cap, no plateau detection">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
while not critic(output).is_perfect():
    output = generate(prompt, feedback=critic(output).feedback)
        ]]></code>
        <note>No cap, no plateau detection — perfect-is-enemy-of-good drives unbounded spend.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Letting the generator and critic share the same model and temperature.</description>
        <reason>Shared prior — generator and critic make the same mistakes, critic rubber-stamps bad output. Either swap models, swap temperatures, or use a rubric prompt that forces a different reasoning path.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Critic returns only a numeric score; loop decides should_continue from a fixed threshold.</description>
        <reason>The critic has more context than the threshold rule. Force the critic to emit should_continue explicitly so domain logic stays in the prompt, not in caller code.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="critic-model-sizing">
      <p>The choice of critic model has a profound impact on both quality and cost. The right model depends on the type of criticism being performed.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Rubric criticism (style, format, completeness, presence of required sections) — use a cheap model (Haiku 4.5, gpt-4.1-mini, Llama-3.3-70B). Constrained classification, no reasoning needed.</item>
        <item>Correctness criticism (math, code, citation accuracy) — use the same tier as the generator. Catching wrong answers requires the same capacity that produces them.</item>
        <item>Mixed criticism — split into two critics: cheap-rubric runs first, strong-correctness only when rubric passes. Cuts critic cost ~60%.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/critic_schema.py" purpose="Pydantic schema for critic output (score, should_continue, feedback)."/>
      <template path="templates/loop.py" purpose="Reference loop with hard cap, delta exit, structured-output critic."/>
    </templates>

